{0 Diagnostics}

Report two classes of problem as diagnostics: {b unresolved links} (so
the user can distinguish resolved from unresolved links without
navigating) and {b duplicate anchor ids} (so ambiguous jump targets are
visible at their source).

{1 Trigger}

Diagnostics are published via [textDocument/publishDiagnostics] after
every index rebuild (i.e. on {b didOpen} and {b didSave}, matching
the current rebuild cadence).

{1 Scope}

Every recognized link form in the document is checked:

{ul
  {- {b Wikilinks}: [[[target]]], [[[target#heading]]],
     [[[target#^blockid]]], [![[embed]]]}
  {- {b Markdown links}: [[text](target)]}
  {- {b Markdown images}: [![alt](img.png)]}
}

External URLs ([https://...], [http://...]) are skipped.

{1:resolution_check Resolution check}

Each link is resolved against the vault index via
{!Oystermark.Vault.Resolve.resolve}.  A link is {e unresolved} when:

{ul
  {- The target note does not exist in the index.}
  {- A heading fragment ([#heading]) does not match any heading in the
     target file (slugified comparison).}
  {- A block-ID fragment ([#^blockid]) does not match any block in the
     target file.}
}

{1:duplicate_ids Duplicate anchor ids}

Anchor ids share a single per-file namespace across the three anchor
kinds — heading slugs, caret block ids, and explicit djot attribute ids
([{#id}]). See {!page-"feature-attribute-anchors"}. Because djot
attribute merge is override (not accumulation), an id that occurs more
than once in a file makes every [#id] reference to it ambiguous.

{ul
  {- The document's anchors are collected from the freshly-parsed content
     (not the stale index entry) via
     {!Oystermark.Vault.Index.extract_headings},
     {!Oystermark.Vault.Index.extract_block_ids}, and
     {!Oystermark.Vault.Index.extract_attr_ids}.}
  {- Anchors are grouped by id string. Any id occurring {e more than
     once} is a duplicate.}
  {- {b Every} occurrence of a duplicated id gets its own diagnostic (not
     just the second and later ones), so all conflicting sites are
     visible.}
  {- The reported range is the anchor node's byte range; an occurrence
     whose location is unknown ([Textloc.none]) is skipped.}
}

This covers both same-kind duplicates (two [{#foo}]) and cross-kind
collisions (a heading whose slug equals a hand-written [{#foo}]).
Heading-vs-heading slug collisions do not arise here because slugs are
auto-deduped during parsing.

{1 Diagnostic shape}

{t
  | Field        | Value                                               |
  |--------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
  | range        | byte range of the link or anchor (see {!page-"feature-utf16-positions"}) |
  | severity     | Warning                                             |
  | source       | ["oystermark"]                                      |
  | message      | human-readable description, e.g. ["unresolved link: note"] or ["duplicate anchor id: foo"] |
}

Resolved links and unique anchor ids produce no diagnostic. Diagnostics
are returned sorted by range start for determinism.

{1 Edge cases}

{ul
  {- {b Empty document}: zero diagnostics.}
  {- {b Self-referencing fragment} ([[[#heading]]]): resolved against
     the current file; unresolved if heading/block not found.}
  {- {b Embed links} ([![[note]]]): treated identically to regular
     wikilinks for diagnostic purposes.}
  {- {b Unique anchor id}: no diagnostic, even when it is never
     referenced.}
  {- {b Duplicate id, some occurrences unlocated}: only the located
     occurrences are reported.}
}
